The Indian industrial sector's transition towards CE practices is in an embryonic stage and needs aggressive improvement (Singh et al., 2018). The Indian leather industry acts as a great employment generator, thus alleviating poverty and earning foreign exchange. According to a report from the Council for Leather Exports, the leather export from India has reached a value of US$ 5.69 billion during 2018-2019. This number reflects that the leather industry's annual economic contribution is significant (Dwivedi et al., 2019). Although the leather industry's economic contribution is substantial, India ranks 168 among 180 countries in the 2020 Environmental Performance Index (EPI report, 2020), which is a major concern for the nation. This report insists that Indian industrial community needs to adopt more eco-friendly practices to improve its image globally. In this connection, CE practices allow the Indian leather industry to reduce the adverse environmental impacts and create a more attractive brand in the world market. In this study, five leather companies (Table 5
                        ) and ten experts (Table 6
                        ) from Indian leather industries are invited to evaluate the inhibitors to CE practices. In this study, the purposive sampling technique was used. Initially, a total of fifteen experts having profound experience and knowledge in CE practices were approached for this study. However, only ten experts showed interest in sharing their knowledge on CE practices. These ten experts have sufficient working experience in leather industries and they know CE practices. According to Lin et al. (2016), a small number of experts would be sufficient in the decision-making analysis if they have more than 10 years of experience in the relevant field. The number of experts used in this study is acceptable. Several earlier studies also used five (Bhatia & Srivastava, 2018) or fewer experts (Rajesh & Ravi, 2015). Fig. 1
                         depicts the framework used in the study.
